*hits pipe*

>>25783334
>How do you do drafts and writing?
Depends. With The Leaves of Fall, due to its schedule, you are all getting a 0 draft, which is essentially my very, very first draft of anything with minimal editing. Normally I write something, then do heavy rounds of edits, often re-writing most of it in the process. But with my current project it's a 0 draft for sure.

>Do you write a scene you were feeling unsatisfied through and continue or do you refuse to get past it until its perfect?
A mix of both. Sometimes, with deadlines, all you can do is put out a 0 draft copy and hope it's okay. But if I have time I'll rewrite scenes plenty. I'm doing it right now.

>Do you just write the general gist of the scenes and improvise or do you just know what will happen in every way?
Again, a mix for me. Sometimes I'll know what the scene is, but that's about it. Then I let my characters guide me to how I want the scene to end/what I want it to mean. Othertimes I tell my characters to follow their fucking lines and do it exactly as I tell them.

>How do you create your characters?
A great question that has a million answers. I often observe people and start imagining stuff about their lives based on what I think they do for a living, what they're wearing, the environment they're in, or what they're doing. And then I start plugging that data into a tone or a scene, and gauge how I think they'd react. And most importantly, I ask myself: what does this character want? What are their goals and triumphs and failures?

Do it with a stranger next time. Imagine a setting and then see how that random person passing by you fits into a setting. Do they come home to a spouse or a TV dinner for one? Are they wealthy or rich? Do they care deeply for their pets, or just use them to distract themslelves from their misery.

I could go on, but I need to get dinner and write some more. If you have questions I'll do my best. Good luck out there lad

>>25783334
Narric here

Most, if not all, of my planning is mental. I have scenes, some key dialogue, plot elements, all floating inside my headspace. When writing, I try and describe/narrate what is happening, and essentially move through the scene at the same pace I write it.

Characters of my own creation are often anywhere from 40-80% mentally visualised, with characterisation built upon within the narrative they inhabit. This is usually where I take notes to ensure characters act/think consistently where possible.

I struggle with motivation, so my main worry is that I'm not actually writing long enough updates for my stories. It also isn't helped by getting new idea sparks constantly taking up prime thinking space in my head, often times diverting me from a previous project. Alongside normal power fantasies, but thats not hmofa related.

Currently while working on "Princess of the Silver Screen," I'm trying to create a railroad for my mind to work in while writing. Sort of a, "I have a scene in my mind, that I need to write," mentality. I get into it very easily with gaming, so I know I can do it.

Anonymous Thu 03 Oct 2019 23:56:50 No.25783607 Report

>>25783334
My writing style's a little weird, and probably not conducive to how the pro's do it, but this is a ultimately a hobby for me. I get an idea for a scene or story in my head, usually in the shower or right before going to bed, or right after waking up, and will build on it until I feel like I got the beats down to write it out. Then after that it's just refining it to where it's readable.

If I'm unsatisfied with a scene, I try to tweak until I'm satisfied, or disregard it and come up with something that I like, and still makes sense within the overall story.

I go in knowing the big picture idea of it, but the details I tend to hash out in the moment of writing.

Creating characters is usually the first thing I come up with in my head along with the concept/idea for a story. My philosophy is you can have the greatest setting and fluff in the world, but if the characters aren't interesting, who gives a shit?

Quoted By:
>>25783334
>>25783334
>How do you do drafts and writing?
I write a draft for each update then go back through and edit/rewrite it. This isn't professional novel writing and I'm not inclined to treat it as such, but I stick with that much as minimum.
>Do you write a scene you were feeling unsatisfied through and continue or do you refuse to get past it until its perfect?
Aiming for perfection is a one way trip to insanity and dissatisfaction. I try to get it in a range I can accept as readable and then move on.
>Do you just write the general gist of the scenes and improvise or do you just know what will happen in every way?
I adapt the scene as I write but I do have goals I aim the story towards. Big goals and small goals, like a particular line that needs to be said to a major plot event.
>How do you create your characters?
They just happen. Sometimes talking to other people they start taking shape, sometimes because I have a story role that needs filling, or they're shaped as I sit down and just start writing.
